ABSTRACT

In this report, I discuss the analysis of neural activity data obtained from experiments conducted on mice in a study by Steinmetz et al. (2019). The data set of these experiments comprise of 18 sessions with a set number of trials where mice made decisions based on a visual stimuli. The objective of this report is to build a predictive model for trial outcomes.

The initial was exploratory data analysis of the experiments. To do this I looked at the data structure across sessions; this includes looking at the varying number of neurons in each session, the number of trials in each session, success rate of the trials across the sessions, and the number of unique brain areas.

Session 10 was the primary session who’s data was used to build the end model.

The next step was data integration. I looked further into the number of neurons in each session, the average spike rate over each session, and the individual success rates of each session. Then, I visually graphed the success rates across each session and mouse, brain areas with neurons recorded in each session, and the change of overall neuron spike rate over time for each session and mouse.

Lastly, predictive models were developed using logistic regression. The first model utilized only the stimulus contrasts, while the second model incorporated the average spike count for each brain area. The models were evaluated based on their misclassification rates, ROC curves, and AUC values.

The results show that Model 2 outperforms Model 1 and a bias guess. The ROC curves and AUC values illustrate the discrimination ability of each model, with higher AUC values indicating better performance.

SECTION 1 INTRODUCTION

This project aims to analyze a data set from a study conducted by Steinmetz et al. (2019). Within the study, Steinmetz et al. focus on experiments performed on 10 mice over 39 sessions. Visual stimuli were presented to the mice on two screens, with varying contrast levels. The mice made decisions based on these stimuli using a wheel, receiving feedback accordingly. Each trial is characterized by feedback type, left and right contrast levels, time bins for spike counts, spike counts of neurons, and brain area. A total of 18 RDS files are provided, each containing data from one session.

This project’s overarching goal is to build a predictive model for trial outcomes using neural activity data and stimuli.

This project felt particularly challenging due to the structure of the data being a folder of .rds files. I found this to be a daunting task to work with at first. Initially, I attempted to read in the data, then put it in a matrix so it would be easier to work with. However, I eventually found that working with the data directly from the folder was easiest.

Due to the large data set with the 18 sessions having many trials within them, I decided it was best to choose a singular session to work with instead of iterating through them all. As such, I mainly focused on session 10 to build the model. This made it so my code ran smoother and would not be excessively large. I chose session 10 for reasons later discussed in this report.

Unfortunately, in the end, I was unable to find a perfect model to predict trial outcomes.

Within this section, the 18 x 2 tibble directly above displays the number of neurons in its respective session. The number of trials per session, the success rate across all sessions, and the number of unique brain areas recorded for each session.

Finding the total number of trials per session is important due to sampling size significance. Because session 10 had the most number of trials, I chose this session to help build my model. Of the trials, because of its sample size, session 10 had the most statistical power, can be generalized most easily, and made it easier to identify patterns within the data.

Next, I considered the success rates of the trials due to the fact that it displays how effective the overal experiment was. For this experiment, it was found to have a success rate of 71.01%. This is significant for both interpreting the data which helped to provide context of the neural activity, but also gives an insight to what the trials/sessions will look like when I eventually look at a specific trial. Additionally, this is a fairly high success rate indicating good quality of the experiment design; if the success rate were low, this could indicate a poor experiment set up or an error in the data collection making the data less useful.

Last, I looked at the number of unique brain areas recorded for each session which also reinforced statistical significance as session 10 had the most number of areas recorded.

Additionally, feedback types and stimuli conditions were also found for the 18 sessions. The code and output of session 1 can be found in the appendix (under exploratory analysis).

Furthermore, the above graph displays the neural activities for session 10 above. There is great variation in the graph changing/zig-zagging greatly with every trial.

Firstly, I fit a logistic regression model to the training data. For this model, there is a misclassification rate of 41.1% on the test data, which indicates the model’s performance is not the greatest. Next, I created a confusion matrix plot visualizing the performance of the model, where the x-axis represents the actual feedback types, the y-axis represents the predicted feedback types, and the color. The intensity represents the frequency of predictions; the color intensity within each cell indicates the frequency or count of instances where the model predicted a specific feedback type given the actual feedback type. The diagonal cells from the top-left to bottom-right represent correct predictions, where the predicted feedback type matches the actual feedback type. For my model, it shows only a few amounts of correct predictions. Unfortunately, there is an abundance of incorrect predictions.

Next, I created a bias of the model. The confusion matrix for this does substantially worse than the model I created with a misclassification rate of 35.5%. I created a confusion matrix plot visualizing the performance of the baseline prediction which furth indicates even less amounts of correct predictions but with even more amounts of incorrect predictions.

Then I created a second model using the same method as the first (logistic model). The difference between the two models are from the dataset used; this model includes average spike count for each brain area in each trial. The rate found for this model was 35.56% and further predicts the feedback type based on the features in the training data (train) after incorporating the average spike count for each brain area in each trial. Model two’s confusion matrix was then made and indicates overall better prediction than model one and the bias as it predict correctly at a higher frequency.

In terms of which is the best model, the ROC curve displays very similar guesses. However, the AUC (Area Under the Curve) is largest with model 2 thus making the better model.

Number of Neurons in Each Session

# Initialize a vector to store the number of neurons in each session
neurons_per_session <- numeric(18)

# Loop through each session
for (i in 1:18) {
  # Extract the spike trains matrix for each trial in the session
  spike_trains <- session[[i]]$spks
  
  # Calculate the number of neurons in the session by summing the number of rows in each trial's spike trains matrix
  neurons_per_session[i] <- sum(sapply(spike_trains, function(x) nrow(x)))
}

get_trail_data <- function(session_id, trail_id){
  spikes <- session[[session_id]]$spks[[trail_id]]
  if (any(is.na(spikes))){
    disp("value missing")
  }

  #trail_tibble <- as_tibble(spikes) %>% set_names(binename) %>%  add_column("brain_area" = session[[session_id]]$brain_area ) %>% group_by(brain_area) %>% summarize( "sum_spikes" =across(everything(),sum),.groups = "drop") 
  trail_tibble <- tibble("neuron_spike" = rowSums(spikes))  %>%  add_column("brain_area" = session[[session_id]]$brain_area ) %>% group_by(brain_area) %>% summarize( region_sum_spike = sum(neuron_spike), region_count = n(),region_mean_spike = mean(neuron_spike)) 
  trail_tibble  = trail_tibble%>% add_column("trail_id" = trail_id) %>% add_column("contrast_left"= session[[session_id]]$contrast_left[trail_id]) %>% add_column("contrast_right"= session[[session_id]]$contrast_right[trail_id]) %>% add_column("feedback_type"= session[[session_id]]$feedback_type[trail_id])
  trail_tibble
}

Data Integration

get_session_data <- function(session_id){
  n_trail <- length(session[[session_id]]$spks)
  trail_list <- list()
  for (trail_id in 1:n_trail){
    trail_tibble <- get_trail_data(session_id,trail_id)
    trail_list[[trail_id]] <- trail_tibble
  }
  session_tibble <- do.call(rbind, trail_list)
  session_tibble <- session_tibble %>% add_column("mouse_name" = session[[session_id]]$mouse_name) %>% add_column("date_exp" = session[[session_id]]$date_exp) %>% add_column("session_id" = session_id) 
  session_tibble
}


session_list = list()
for (session_id in 1: 18){
  session_list[[session_id]] <- get_session_data(session_id)
}
full_tibble <- do.call(rbind, session_list)
full_tibble$success <- full_tibble$feedback_type == 1
full_tibble$success <- as.numeric(full_tibble$success)
full_tibble$contrast_diff <- abs(full_tibble$contrast_left-full_tibble$contrast_right)
binename <- paste0("bin", as.character(1:40))

get_trail_functional_data <- function(session_id, trail_id){
  spikes <- session[[session_id]]$spks[[trail_id]]
  if (any(is.na(spikes))){
    disp("value missing")
  }

  trail_bin_average <- matrix(colMeans(spikes), nrow = 1)
  colnames(trail_bin_average) <- binename
  trail_tibble  = as_tibble(trail_bin_average)%>% add_column("trail_id" = trail_id) %>% add_column("contrast_left"= session[[session_id]]$contrast_left[trail_id]) %>% add_column("contrast_right"= session[[session_id]]$contrast_right[trail_id]) %>% add_column("feedback_type"= session[[session_id]]$feedback_type[trail_id])
  
  trail_tibble
}
get_session_functional_data <- function(session_id){
  n_trail <- length(session[[session_id]]$spks)
  trail_list <- list()
  for (trail_id in 1:n_trail){
    trail_tibble <- get_trail_functional_data(session_id,trail_id)
    trail_list[[trail_id]] <- trail_tibble
  }
  session_tibble <- as_tibble(do.call(rbind, trail_list))
  session_tibble <- session_tibble %>% add_column("mouse_name" = session[[session_id]]$mouse_name) %>% add_column("date_exp" = session[[session_id]]$date_exp) %>% add_column("session_id" = session_id) 
  session_tibble
}
session_list = list()

Predictive Modelling

Feedback Type vs Decision

n_obs = length(session[[10]]$feedback_type)

dat = tibble(
    feedback_type = as.factor(session[[10]]$feedback_type),
    decision = rep('name', n_obs),
    avg_spikes = rep(0, n_obs)
)

for (i in 1:n_obs){
    # decision 
    if (session[[10]]$contrast_left[i] > session[[10]]$contrast_right[i]){
        dat$decision[i] = '1' 
    } else if (session[[10]]$contrast_left[i] < session[[10]]$contrast_right[i]){
        dat$decision[i] = '2' 
    } else if (session[[10]]$contrast_left[i] == session[[10]]$contrast_right[i] 
               & session[[10]]$contrast_left[i] == 0){
        dat$decision[i] = '3' 
    } else{
        dat$decision[i] = '4' 
    }
    
    # avg_spks
    spks.trial = session[[10]]$spks[[i]]
    total.spikes = apply(spks.trial, 1, sum)
    dat$avg_spikes[i] = mean(total.spikes)
}

dat$decision = as.factor(dat$decision)
summary(dat)
##  feedback_type decision   avg_spikes

##                3:113    Median :1.191  
##                4: 33    Mean   :1.188  
##                         3rd Qu.:1.327

‘1’: If the contrast of the left stimulus is greater than the contrast of the right stimulus. ‘2’: If the contrast of the right stimulus is greater than the contrast of the left stimulus. ‘3’: If both left and right contrasts are zero. ‘4’: If both left and right contrasts are equal but non-zero.

a confusion matrix plot visualizing the performance of the model, where the x-axis represents the actual feedback types, the y-axis represents the predicted feedback types, and the color intensity represents the frequency of predictions.

The color intensity within each cell indicates the frequency or count of instances where the model predicted a specific feedback type (y-axis) given the actual feedback type (x-axis).

The diagonal cells from the top-left to bottom-right represent correct predictions, where the predicted feedback type matches the actual feedback type.

Off-diagonal cells represent incorrect predictions, where the predicted feedback type does not match the actual feedback type.

average_spike_area<-function(i.t,this_session){
  spk.trial = this_session$spks[[i.t]]
  area= this_session$brain_area
  spk.count=apply(spk.trial,1,sum)
  spk.average.tapply=tapply(spk.count, area, mean)
  return(spk.average.tapply)
}

n_area = length(unique(session[[10]]$brain_area))
spk_area = matrix(rep(0, n_obs * n_area), n_obs, n_area)
for (i in 1:n_obs){
    spk_area[i,] = average_spike_area(i, session[[10]])
}

spk_area = as_tibble(spk_area)
colnames(spk_area)= unique(session[[10]]$brain_area)

Which Model is Better

# Model 1
pr = prediction(pred1, test$feedback_type)
prf <- performance(pr, measure = "tpr", x.measure = "fpr")
auc <- performance(pr, measure = "auc")
auc <- auc@y.values[[1]]

# Model 2
pr = prediction(pred2, test$feedback_type)
prf2 <- performance(pr, measure = "tpr", x.measure = "fpr")
auc2 <- performance(pr, measure = "auc")
auc2 <- auc2@y.values[[1]]

# Bias Guess
pred0 = pred1 * 0 + 1
pr = prediction(pred0, test$feedback_type)
prf0 <- performance(pr, measure = "tpr", x.measure = "fpr")
auc0 <- performance(pr, measure = "auc")
auc0 <- auc0@y.values[[1]]

plot(prf2, ,col = 'red', main = 'ROC curve')
plot(prf, add = TRUE, col = 'blue')
plot(prf0, add = TRUE, col = 'green')
legend("bottomright", legend=c("Model 1", "Model 2", "Bias Guess"), col=c("blue", "red", 'green'), lty=1:1, 
       cex=0.8)

print(c(auc, auc2, auc0))
